studyFeedback: I have been to meetings like those that seemed to be discussed in the article. In my organization, we tend to naturally do some of the outlined suggestions such as only inviting those relevant to the meeting. Most in our organization that would and do attend necessary meetings tend to be high performers anyway, so our main issue is meeting length. We have done too many marathons over the years, as many of us actually work quite independently from each other and departments are small, so there is some burn out from the past. We would put off meeting, but then when we did meet, there would be a lot to discuss piled up. Now we have learned to hold more regular and concise meetings to avoid this, and have been able to be much more effective and less dreading these long and tedious meetings.
I enjoyed that - ty

studyFeedback: I kept thinking of how in my organization, the amount and types of meetings are often dictated by those not involved in those meetings.

I apologize in advance if I'm incorrect, but I'm quite sure I never received any instructions that said I needed to use the GenAI when reading the article.  I normally don't use GenAI when reading an article so I didn't use it at all when reading this article.  I understood all of the concepts and didn't need it for anything, so I didn't use it.  I consider my reading comprehension abilities to be quite high.  I'm accustomed to reading academic articles such as these in my current role at work, and in my past roles as an academic Librarian in both Community College and University settings.  This explains my responses in sections 3 and 4.  The article was thoroughly enjoyable to read, and I intend to utilize some of the information I learned from it for the meetings I organize in the future.  Thank you for the opportunity to assist you with your research.
